     <div name="helpText">
       <p>In general, to find the probability that when flipping <m>n</m> coins, exactly <m>k</m> land heads, we must determine 
         <me>P(E) = \frac{\text{number of outcomes in event E}}{\text{number of total outcomes}}</me>
         where <m>E</m> is the number of ways to land <m>k</m> heads, and the total number of outcomes is the number of ways (with any number of heads from <m>0</m> to <m>n</m>) that <m>n</m> coins can be flipped.</p>
         <ul>
           <li>the numerator will be found from the <m>n^{\text{th}}</m> row of Pascal's Triangle. The row number corresponds to the number of coins, <m>n</m> (recall that the top row corresponds to row <m>0</m>). We count across the row, assuming that we start with 0 heads and counting up by one each column to find the correct value (since Pascal's Triangle is symmetric, this is equivalent to starting with all heads and counting down).
             <image source='doenet:cid=bafkreif4xsvpzw75msd7lmjp45n6z2cdcwp6jw4e2nuiuyoa5q2mroi4fi' description="graphical representation of Pascal's Triangle" asfilename='PascalsTriangle.png' size="small" mimeType='image/png' />
           </li>
           <li>alternatively, the numerator can be found by computing the number of <ref uri="https://open.lib.umn.edu/probability/chapter/topic-1-5/">combinations</ref> of <m>k</m> objects from a set of size <m>n</m>, using
             <me>C(n,k) = \frac{n!}{k!(n - k)!}</me></li>
           <li>the denominator is <m>2^n</m>, or the total number of possible coin tosses for <m>n</m> coins.</li>
         </ul>
    </div>
  </feedback>


<!--*********************************************
            Hint
**********************************************-->
<hint name="helpSection"><title>Worked Example</title>

<p>Here is a similar worked example:</p> 
<example newNameSpace>
<p><em>If <m>$n</m> coins are tossed, what is the probability that exactly <m>$k</m> will land 'heads'?</em></p> 

<setup>
  <math name="n">12</math>
  <math name="k">6</math>
  <math name="numerator">$n!/($k!($n - $k)!)</math>
  <math name="probOfKHeads">($n!/($k!($n-$k)!))/(2^$n)</math>
</setup>

<p><alert><em>Solution.</em></alert></p>
<p>The probability of rolling <m>k</m> heads on <m>n</m> coin flips is given by
  <me>P(H = k) = \frac{C(n,k)}{2^n} = \frac{\binom{n}{k}}{2^n}</me></p>
<ul>
  <li>The numerator is 
    <md>
      <mrow>\binom{n}{k} \amp= \binom{$n}{$k} \amp\text{compute binomial coefficient}</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp=$numerator</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp=$numerator{simplify}</mrow>
    </md></li>
  <li>The denominator is <m>2^{$n} = <math name="denominator" simplify>2^$n</math></m></li>
  <li>The probability is
    <me>P(H = $k) = <math>$numerator{simplify}/$denominator</math> = $probOfKHeads{simplify}</me></li>
</ul>
  
</example>

</hint>

<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->  
<solution>
<p>The probability of rolling <m>k</m> heads on <m>n</m> coin flips is given by
  <me>P(H = k) = \frac{C(n,k)}{2^n} = \frac{\binom{n}{k}}{2^n}</me></p>
<ul>
  <li>The numerator is 
    <md>
      <mrow>\binom{n}{k} \amp= \binom{$n}{$k} \amp\text{compute binomial coefficient}</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp=$numerator</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp=$numerator{simplify}</mrow>
    </md></li>
  <li>The denominator is <m>2^{$n} = <math name="denominator" simplify>2^$n</math></m></li>
  <li>The probability is
    <me>P(H = $k) = <math>$numerator{simplify}/$denominator</math> = $probOfKHeads{simplify}</me></li>
</ul>

</solution>
</problem>



